This was/is a great movie and there is actually a lot of truth to this on how the "head of households" actions can "change" how your "significant other" and/or children feel about, and react towards, you.  I use more open terms, as it sends a really good and quite truthful, message for however your household is set up. If both parents work, then put both yourselves in the "mans shoes" and see how it is probably effecting and possibly hurting, your children. The title is kind of deceiving, as I wouldn't call them losers, just lost site of their priorities over time and quit "listening" to their spouses, and being their for their families, not intentionally.  I feel that it is a must see, as we can lose track and veer off course so easy and not even realize how it effects others.  It is a lighthearted comedy, but I feel it carries a great message.

There were moments when I had to pause it, take a breath and play it again. Lol. I really tried to like it, but the profanity made it ok. I did enjoy the chemistry been Tika Sumpter and John Stamos. They had an interesting journey together and I liked the storyline between the guys. Love is a beautiful thing.

About five lines of actual writing.  The rest?  Profanity. Most scenes begin and end with the "F" word, then there's about 3 more in between. Add a cast of unsympathetic characters (less one), vulgarity and crass humor & that's your movie.  I did enjoy the chemistry between John Stamos and his love interest, so I had to mute and FF through everything else.  I'm not joking!  I paid for it & wanted to get my $3.99 worth!  Lol.  Even that was only worth about $1.20.

I don't know why some people gave this one such a low rating, it was actually one of the better chick flicks I have seen recently. nice to see John Stamos hasn't lost his talent, and the dynamics of the cast was fantastic, if I can do one benevolent thing, I would recommend this movie to any couple wanting a movie night!
